Jacob wants to buy some specialty fabric to make his kindergardner Kamala a halloween costume. The fabric store tells him that the fabric costs \displaystyle{8.61}\ \frac{\text{dollars}}{{\text{yard}^{{2}}}}. Note about this unitNote: Typically, when a fabric store says "yard", they actually mean "square yards". In this problem, I have written it out in the correct format: \displaystyle\text{yards}^{{2}}


Jacob is sure he saw this advertised online for \displaystyle{0.79}\frac{\text{cents}}{{\text{inch}^{{2}}}}, and he wants to know if it is a better deal in the store or online. He will take a minute to convert the price from \displaystyle\frac{\text{dollars}}{{\text{yard}^{{2}}}} to \displaystyle\frac{\text{cents}}{{\text{inch}^{{2}}}} to see which is the better deal.


Jacob knows the following facts:





\displaystyle{1}\ \text{yard}={3}\ \text{feet}


\displaystyle{1}\ \text{ft}={12}\ \text{inches}


\displaystyle{1}\ \text{dollar}={100}\ \text{cents}

Jacob will perform the conversion by starting with the measured price as a fraction. Choose the correct unit fraction to multiply by in order to complete the conversion:

\displaystyle\frac{{{8.61}\ \text{dollars}}}{{\text{yard}^{{2}}}}\astAB0\displaystyle\astAB1\displaystyle\astAB2\displaystyle\astAB3\displaystyle\astAB4


///


The correct expression is:


\displaystyle\frac{{{8.61}\ \text{dollars}}}{{\text{yard}^{{2}}}}\ast\frac{{{1}\ \text{yd}}}{{{3}\ \text{ft}}}\ast\frac{{{1}\ \text{yd}}}{{{3}\ \text{ft}}}\ast\frac{{{1}\ \text{ft}}}{{{12}\ \text{in}}}\ast\frac{{{1}\ \text{ft}}}{{{12}\ \text{in}}}\ast\frac{{{100}\ \text{cents}}}{{{1}\ \text{dollar}}}


What is the final result, rounded to two decimal places?


Answer: AB5 \displaystyle\frac{\text{cents}}{{\text{inch}^{{2}}}}


///


If Jacob wants to save the most money, should he shop at the store or online?


Answer: 



Online 


The Store
